@alreadydone I changed things to work with `Iio` instead of `Π o <`, and now I actually think `Π o <` is better, because `Iio δ` is in a higher universe than `δ`. `Ordinal.sup` requires the range universe to be at least as high as the domain universe, but if the domain is `Iio ω` for example than we have to lift the output to universe `1`. With `Ordinal.bsup`, if we index with `Π o < ω`  then lean resolves with `ω : Ordinal.{0}`, and same thing when we index with any ordinal in the same universe as the range.

I pushed this not-done version, the problem starts at `isClub_sInter`. If we define `g` without lifting the output, we can't resolve the universe contraints of `sup g`, because `u` could be `0`. Then everything after that would have to deal with many lifts. Unless I'm missing something this makes `sup` much harder to work with than `bsup`, and I don't think its worth it. What's more, we should keep things working with the same definitions everywhere, so I would rather not use `Iio` for the domain of a sequence anywhere.
If that's okay with you I will revert these changes.

